 of elements from   Elizabeth   and   Mary ;  in part a feminine equivalent of   Elmer ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Elin","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Elen ."],"variants":[{"name":"Elen","meanings":["form of   Helen  , now also used outside Wales. It is identical with the Welsh vocabulary word <i>elen</i> ‘nymph’, but this is unlikely to be the origin. It is found in Welsh texts from an early period as an equivalent of <i>Helen</i>, for example as the name of the mother of Constantine, finder of the True Cross."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1357051,"age":33,"year":"1495","julianDay":2267098,"description":"Russians forces invade Sweden.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1702078,"age":33,"year":"1495","toYear":"1497","julianDay":2267098,"title":"The Russo-Swedish War","description":"While in an alliance with Grand Prince Ivan III of Moscow, King Hans of Denmark and Norway invaded Sweden and was declared King of Sweden.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Russo-Swedish_War_(1495%E2%80%931497)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Swedish War","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1702079,"age":58,"year":"1520","julianDay":2276228,"title":"The Stockholm Bloodbath","description":"A mass execution of Swedish nobles by Danish king Christian II is known as the Stockholm Bloodbath. Christian II invaded Sweden in 1519 and took hold of Stockholm in September 1520. Over 80 nobles were executed for heresy on November 8 and 9. The outrage from the executions led to the Swedish removal of support of the Kalmar Union.","url":"https://www.britannica.com/event/Stockholm-Bloodbath","urlTitle":"Britannica - Stockholm Bloodbath","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1702080,"age":61,"year":"1523","julianDay":2277324,"title":"Swedish War of Liberation","description":"The Swedish War of Liberation was a civil war led by nobleman Gustav Vasa. As Christian II heard of the rebellion, he confronted Vasa's men, who won the battle at Brunbacks Ferry. Christian II was defeated by the Swedes in Stockholm and a truce was agreed upon. Vasa was given as a hostage as a show of good faith until the treaty was signed. The Danish King did not keep his word and Vasa was held as a prisoner for two years until his escape. A bounty was placed on Vasa's head. Vasa worked to inspire many to join his cause and lived under disguise until the Danes surrendered in 1525.","url":"https://www.sweden.org.za/swedish-monarchy-gustav-vasa.html","urlTitle":"Sweden.org - Swedish Monarchy Gustav Vasa","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1702085,"age":78,"year":"1540","julianDay":2283533,"title":"First Full Swedish Translation of the Bible","description":"The first full Swedish translation of the Bible, known as the Gustav Bible, was completed by Olaus Petri and Laurentius Andreae and published in 1540.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1702086,"age":82,"year":"1544","julianDay":2284994,"title":"Sweden Becomes Lutheran Nation","description":"Sweden officially declared itself a Lutheran nation in 1544.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Elna Elin Persdotter was born in 1462, in Skalmsjö, Västernorrland, Sweden, her father, Per Skute Tre Snäckor, was 22 and her mother, Kerstin Persson, was 18. She had at least 1 son and 2 daughters with Esbjörn Öndesson. She died in 1550, in her hometown, at the age of 88."},"et":{"1462–1550":"1462–1550","1460–1525":"1460–1525","1475–1550":"1475–1550","1488–Female":"1488–Surnud","1500–1560":"1500–1560","1440–1500":"1440–1500","1445–Female":"1445–Surnud","1462":"1462","1550":"1550","1495":"1495","1440":"1440","1560":"1560","1460":"1460","1525":"1525","1523":"1523","1500":"1500","1544":"1544","1445":"1445","1488":"1488","1520":"1520","1475":"1475","1497":"1497","1540":"1540","about 1488":"umbes 1488","Skalmsjö, Anundsjö, Västernorrland, Sverige":"Skalmsjö, Västernorrland, Rootsi","Skalmsjö, Västernorrland, Sweden":"Skalmsjö, Västernorrland, Rootsi","By, Norrbärke, Kopparberg, 